{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.74,0.02,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22317"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44874"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman with a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus not requiring insulin has undergone trans-sphenoidal excision of a pituitary adenoma. During the immediate postoperative period in the high dependency unit she develops polyuria with a urine output of 600ml over 2 hours. Her blood pressure is 120/80mmHg, pulse 84/min and respiratory rate 14/min. Her serum electrolytes show a sodium level of 150mEq/L (135-145mEq/L) and potassium level of 4.1mEq/L (3.5-5mEq/L). A random blood glucose is taken and is 5.6mmol/L (5.5-11mmol/L). Her serum osmolality is 305mOsm/kg (275-295mOsm/kg) and urine osmolarity is completed is 90mOsmol/kg (\u0026lt;100mOsmol/kg).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["10ml/kg IV fluid bolus","IV desmopressin","IV potassium","Insulin","PO glucose gel"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes insipidus is the common endocrine dysfunction following trans-sphenoidal hypophysectomy. The diagnosis of diabetes insipidus is supported by a high urine output, raised serum osmolarity and low specific gravity of the urine. This is due to reduced water resorption from the kidneys back into circulation resulting in polydipsia, polyuria and electrolyte disturbances (particularly hypernatraemia). Diabetes insipidus can be further classified into neurogenic or nephrogenic, dependent upon the cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic diabetes insipidus: \u003C/strong\u003ELack of anti-diuretic hormone (ADH) production from the posterior pituitary gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrogenic diabetes insipidus: \u003C/strong\u003ELack of renal responsiveness to ADH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurogenic diabetes insipidus should be treated with vasopressin subcutaneously or desmopressin IV. Intranasal vasopressin is inappropriate due to the nasal packs immediately post operation but may be required if DI persists. In neurogenic diabetes insipidus, urine osmolarity should increase following administration of vasopressin or desmopressin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther causes of high urine output include diuresis secondary to hyperglycaemia, mannitol or crystalloid administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV fluid bolus \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate if the patient continues to produce copious amounts of urine and becomes hypotension as a result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV Potassium \u003C/strong\u003Eis inappropriate in this patient as the potassium level is within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inappropriate intervention as blood glucose levels are within normal limits and administration may result in a hypoglycaemic episode.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPO glucose gel \u003C/strong\u003Eis not appropriate given blood glucose levels are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Central diabetes insipidus is a common complication following pituitary surgery."],"references":["Almalki MH, Ahmad MM, Brema I, Almehthel M, AlDahmani KM, Mahzari M, Beshyah SA. Management of Diabetes Insipidus following Surgery for Pituitary and Suprasellar Tumours. Sultan Qaboos Univ Med J. 2021 Aug;21(3):354-364. doi: 10.18295/squmj.4.2021.010. Epub 2021 Aug 29. PMID: 34522399; PMCID: PMC8407907."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22317"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22317"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-06T12:06:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-07-06T12:06:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t